---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';
import { site, pageTitle, description } from '../../content';
const path = '/alternatives/tinyemail-alternative';
const title = pageTitle(site, 'alternatives/tinyemail-alternative');
const desc = description(site, 'alternatives/tinyemail-alternative');
const tools = [
  { name: 'Postscript', best: 'SMS-native Shopify cart and lifecycle messaging', pros: 'SMS workflows, replies, and consent-oriented operations', cons: 'Email lifecycle may need a separate platform', price: 'Verify current message and platform pricing', source: 'https://postscript.io/' },
  { name: 'Attentive', best: 'Larger brands with a dedicated SMS growth program', pros: 'Managed SMS acquisition and segmentation depth', cons: 'May exceed a smaller team’s operating needs', price: 'Verify current contract and messaging pricing', source: 'https://www.attentive.com/pricing' },
  { name: 'Omnisend', best: 'SMB stores wanting bundled email, SMS, and push', pros: 'Fast multichannel ecommerce workflows', cons: 'Channel costs and collision rules need governance', price: 'Verify current contact and channel pricing', source: 'https://www.omnisend.com/pricing/' },
  { name: 'Klaviyo', best: 'Stores coordinating SMS with detailed email and product behavior', pros: 'Rich Shopify events across email and SMS', cons: 'Profile pricing and consent complexity can grow', price: 'Verify current contact and feature pricing', source: 'https://www.klaviyo.com/pricing' },
  { name: 'Sequenzy', best: 'Email lifecycle beside a specialist SMS sender', pros: 'Focused welcome, education, post-purchase, and winback sequences', cons: 'Not a direct SMS replacement; validate the handoff', price: 'Verify current plan and integration coverage', source: 'https://sequenzy.io/' },
];
const faqs = [
  { question: 'Why replace TinyEmail for Shopify SMS?', answer: 'Common reasons include unclear message economics, insufficient quiet-hour or consent controls, weak Shopify event context, or a need to separate SMS urgency from email lifecycle education.' },
  { question: 'Can email permission be reused for SMS?', answer: 'No. Treat SMS consent separately. Preserve opt-in source, timestamp, message type, opt-outs, quiet hours, and suppression state.' },
  { question: 'How should I migrate?', answer: 'Export and validate consent first, rebuild cart recovery, test STOP handling and quiet hours, then add launch, replenishment, and winback flows with a collision calendar.' },
];
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={path}><ArticleSchema title={title} description={desc} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} /><main class="container py-14 md:py-20"><a href="/alternatives" class="link text-sm">← All alternatives</a><p class="badge mt-6">Shopify SMS migration</p><h1 class="hero-title mt-5 max-w-5xl">Best TinyEmail alternatives for Shopify SMS</h1><p class="mt-7 max-w-3xl text-xl leading-9 text-cyan-100">The best TinyEmail replacement depends on whether you need an SMS-native sender, a bundled email-and-SMS platform, or a dedicated email lifecycle layer beside SMS. Do not choose by logo alone: compare consent, quiet hours, message economics, and Shopify event fidelity.</p><section class="mt-12 max-w-5xl overflow-x-auto rounded-2xl border border-white/[0.08]"><table class="w-full text-left"><thead><tr><th>Platform</th><th>Best fit</th><th>Pros</th><th>Tradeoff</th></tr></thead><tbody>{tools.map((tool, i) => <tr class={i === 0 ? 'highlight-row' : ''}><td class="font-semibold text-white">{tool.name}</td><td>{tool.best}</td><td>{tool.pros}</td><td>{tool.cons}</td></tr>)}</tbody></table></section><article class="prose-shopify mt-14 max-w-4xl"><h2>Why merchants replace TinyEmail for SMS</h2><p>SMS is a scarce interruption channel, not a shorter email. A cart reminder, launch alert, replenishment text, and service message need different timing, consent expectations, and suppression rules. The migration should begin by mapping those message classes and deciding which platform owns each one.</p><p>Model total cost as platform fee plus carrier or message fee plus discount cost and operator time. A text that needs a deep coupon to convert may reduce contribution margin even when an attribution dashboard reports revenue. Compare incremental orders, opt-outs, complaints, and full-price repeat behavior.</p><h2>Platform notes</h2>{tools.map((tool, i) => <section><h3>{i + 1}. {tool.name}</h3><p><strong>Best for:</strong> {tool.best}. <strong>Pros:</strong> {tool.pros}. <strong>Cons:</strong> {tool.cons}. <strong>Pricing:</strong> {tool.price}. Review the <a href={tool.source} target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">official source</a> and include message volume, contacts, seats, consent tooling, and integration work.</p><table><tbody><tr><th>Consent test</th><td>Can the team prove opt-in source and timestamp, honor STOP, enforce quiet hours, and preserve exclusions?</td></tr><tr><th>Collision test</th><td>Can the stack prevent the same offer arriving by SMS and email in the same intent window?</td></tr></tbody></table></section>)}<h2>Migration checklist</h2><ol><li>Export SMS consent, opt-outs, timestamps, source, quiet-hour settings, segments, templates, and live flows.</li><li>Do not import email-only contacts into SMS.</li><li>Rebuild cart recovery first and test purchase exits, STOP behavior, and quiet hours.</li><li>Add launch, replenishment, and winback paths only after consent and suppression QA.</li><li>Measure incremental orders, cost per incremental order, opt-outs, complaints, discount depth, and repeat quality.</li></ol><h2>Verdict</h2><p>Choose Postscript for SMS-native Shopify operations, Attentive for a managed large-scale SMS program, Omnisend for bundled multichannel workflows, Klaviyo for deep email-and-SMS commerce behavior, and Sequenzy when email lifecycle should remain a deliberate layer beside SMS. The safest migration is the one that improves ownership and consent visibility, not merely the one that changes the sender.</p></article><FaqSection faqs={faqs} /><p class="mt-12 text-slate-300">Continue with <a class="link" href="/apps">app profiles</a>, <a class="link" href="/compare">comparisons</a>, and <a class="link" href="/guides">SMS operator guides</a>.</p></main></BaseLayout>
